05143nam a22007935i 9780823289622DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232896227 a10.1515/97808232896222doi  a(DE-B1597)572943  a(OCoLC)1199057143  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0090002bisacsh04a809.892822231 aKidd, Kenneth B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTheory for Beginners :bChildren's Literature as Critical Thought /cKenneth B. Kidd. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b6 b/w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Children's Literature Otherwise -- t1 Philosophy for Children -- t2 Theory for Beginners -- t3 Literature for Minors -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter centuries of ignoring the child, some philosophy now considers the child an ideal practitioner as well as subject. This is evident especially in the Philosophy for Children, or P4C, movement. Offering a novel take on this phenomenon, Theory for Beginners explores how philosophy and theory draw on children's literature and have even come to resemble it in their strategies for cultivating the child and/or the beginner.Since its inception in the 1970s, P4C has affirmed children's literature as important philosophical work as part of its commitment to keeping philosophy fresh and relevant. Theory, meanwhile, has invested in children's classics, especially Lewis Carroll's Alice books, and has also developed a literature for beginners that resembles children's literature in significant ways. After examining the P4C movement, author Kenneth B. Kidd turns his critical eye to theory for beginners as exemplified in the form of the multitude of illustrated guides. If philosophy is for children and theory is for beginners, he argues, then children's literature might also be described as a literature for minors, and perhaps even a minor literature as theorized by Deleuze and Guattari. Examining everything from the work of the rise of French Theory in the United States to the crucial pedagogies offered in children's picture books, from Alison Bechdel's graphic memoir Are You My Mother? and Lemony Snicket's A Series of Unfortunate Events to studies of queer childhood, Kidd deftly reveals the way in which children may learn from philosophy and vice versa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChildren and philosophy. 0aChildren's literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aCritical thinking in children. 0aYoung adult literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Children's & Young Adult Literature.2bisacsh  aP4C.  aTheory.  achildhood studies.  aphilosophy, children's literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311072271040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823289622zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823289622423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823289622.jpg  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK 